explanation:
All other for loops in the provided code conform to the listed clauses of MISRA C 2023 Rule 14.2 and therefore do not require investigation: 

- for (i = 0; i < idx_first_rdata; i++) { response[i] = frame[i]; idx_response++; }
  - The first clause initializes the single loop counter (i). The second clause uses only the loop counter and the precomputed idx_first_rdata (not modified in the loop body). The third clause (i++) modifies only the loop counter. The body does modify idx_response, but that object is not used in the loop clauses.

- for (i = 0; i < length; i++) { response[idx_response] = (unsigned char) msg[i]; idx_response++; }
  - The first clause initializes the single loop counter (i). The second clause uses only the loop counter and length (length is not modified in the loop body). The third clause (i++) modifies only the loop counter. The body modifies idx_response, but idx_response is not used in any loop clause.

- for (i = 0; i < MAX_CLIENTS; i++) { isock = CLIENT_SOCKS[i]; ... }
  - The first clause initializes the single loop counter (i). The second clause uses only the loop counter and a compile-time constant MAX_CLIENTS (not modified in the loop body). The third clause (i++) modifies only the loop counter. The body reads CLIENT_SOCKS[i] and may call send_all, but nothing used in the loop clauses is modified by the loop body.

In each of the above, there is only one loop counter, it is initialised in the first clause, the second clause does not use objects that are modified in the loop body, and the third clause modifies only the loop counter — therefore they meet the requirements of Rule 14.2.

The for loop in send_all is flagged because its third clause uses the variable 'ret', which is assigned inside the loop body; that makes the third clause depend on an object modified by the loop body and thus is a potential violation of the rule and should be investigated.
